"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.4.3\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.4.3</span> Cage</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">סוּגַר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(sugar)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek19:9\">EZK 19:9</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">κάρταλλος</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kartallos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir11:30\">SIR 11:30</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0001_dovesincage.png\" alt=\"Doves in a cage, awaiting to be sold in the temple and to be used as sacrifice\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Doves in a cage, awaiting to be sold in the temple and to be used as sacrifice (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>The cage was a kind of basket, woven loosely of cane or sticks. It had a top or door that could be closed. When a bird or other prey was caught alive, it was confined in the cage. Sometimes the basket itself served as a kind of trap.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The Hebrew word <em>sugar</em> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek19:9\">EZK 19:9</a> probably refers to a kind of wooden collar put on prisoners (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.1.1 Yoke&lt;REALIA:1.1.1&gt;</a>). However, perhaps because the prophet pictures Judah’s king as a captured lion here, most translations render it “cage.” A few translations (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"German Common Language Version (Gute Nachricht Bibel)\">GECL</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Italian Common Language Version\">ITCL</abbr>) have “collar” or “yoke.” <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jerusalem Bible (1985)\">NJB</abbr> has “shackled.”</p>\n<p>Sometimes a captive bird could be used as a lure to capture a larger animal. The bird was tied inside the basket. When the prey entered the basket to take the bait, the basket was closed upon it by some device. It is presumably this interpretation of <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir11:30\">SIR 11:30</a> that has caused <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> to render the first half of this verse as “A proud person is a decoy to lure you into danger.” Other translations omit the element of the lure; for example, the New American Bible (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New American Bible (1970)\">NAB</abbr>) has “Though he seem like a bird confined in a cage” (similarly <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Italian Common Language Version\">ITCL</abbr>).</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
